description: Bees on angelica

A black and yellow mystery bee. The shrub where the bee was foraging presented difficult shooting conditions so the best I can offer is several photos (some not sharp) to try to help with an id.  Not B. sitkensis - hair on thorax is pure yellow, not a mixture of yellow and black.  The hair seems too long and shaggy to be B vosnesenskii. Looks like there is a clear band of yellow on S4 and a fringe on S3 (photo 3). Always on the lookout for a hint towards B. caliginous, but I could only get a glimpse of malar length (photo 4). My repertoire of black and yellow bees is far from complete but I don't know what else this might be.

description: Grasshopper Mountain, Tulameen, BC, Canada

On Sedum sp. Almost immobile, moving only very slowly. Strongly recurved terminal tergite confirms this as a cuckoo bumble bee. Note dark vertex, flagellum twice as long as scape, black face which are all typical of B. flavidus. Foraging with B. ternarius and B. vagans.

Bumble Bees of NA describes these bees as small, and this doesn't match the individuals I've seen here. (That is to say: individuals here seem to be medium to large sized.) Black hair on head, orange hairs at tip of abdomen and hairy round hind tibia all suggest male flavidus to me.  Flower is cultivated, species unknown to me.

description: Male. Orange at tip of abdomen. On cultivated aster.

Another mystery for me. I am always on the lookout for unusual black & yellow bombus in the hopes that I might see caliginosus. This bee was buried in my files from last spring. The black hairs on the face and the absence of strong yellow markings on the abdomen puzzle me. There is a weak yellow fringe at the sides and on the sternal surface. Hair is shaggy. I can't tell whether I'm seeing a corbicula. It was a very dark day so exposures are poor but I'm posting this because the bee seems unusual.

My best guess - I can't see the hind femur and the shape of the abdomen seems more bulbous than I usually see with Psithyrus. I didn't get a view if the head but the first photo shows a peek at black hair. If I'm right this is the first I've seen with T1 - 4 completely yellow, but that seems to be one of the documented variations for a male.

Story time. Bee rescue and then id dilemma. This bee caught my eye because she seemed to be in distress, trying to feed on a buttercup. She was crawling on and over it and nearby buds and seemed unable to fly. I picked the stem, placed it and her on a skunk cabbage leaf and wrapped her loosely to be carried to a nearby patch of Rubus in bloom. She had just enough energy to buzz a bit. I placed her on a Rubus bloom and she immediately began to forage. When I looked at these photos I realized that id was less clear than I expected: hind tibia concave, hair longer than short and a bit shaggy, bottom of thorax yellow, a double band of yellow at ?T4/5 broken by a notch, and hair on head black. Closest would be a worker B rufocinctus of a form I haven't seen here but which has been observed in the lower mainland. Only rufocinctus for me to date here was a form with red band: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/53230699  July 2020. Photos presented in chronological order.
Not confident of ID. I do not see any yellow above antennal base as is typical of B.insularis. Foraging on chives. Prince George, BC, Canada.
